Haven't I lost enough today?

91
00:04:18,287 --> 00:04:22,890
Well, the guy at the store said
this one is great.

92
00:04:22,892 --> 00:04:24,859
Oh! Oh, the guy!

93
00:04:24,861 --> 00:04:26,827
Oh, pardon me.

94
00:04:26,829 --> 00:04:28,462
I-I didn't realize
you'd spoken to the guy.

95
00:04:28,464 --> 00:04:30,030
Yeah, tell me,

96
00:04:30,032 --> 00:04:32,600
did the guy choose one
with a 4K display

97
00:04:32,602 --> 00:04:34,001
and a Thunderbolt port?

98
00:04:34,003 --> 00:04:35,202
Yes.
Yeah?

99
00:04:35,204 --> 00:04:36,370
D-Did the guy make sure

100
00:04:36,372 --> 00:04:39,140
that this has a one-terabyte
solid-state drive?

101
00:04:39,142 --> 00:04:40,674
Yes.
Yeah? Oh, well,

102
00:04:40,676 --> 00:04:43,878
was this guy Rick from
Computer Solutions on Colorado?

103
00:04:43,880 --> 00:04:44,845
Yes.

104
00:04:44,847 --> 00:04:46,213
Yeah, well,
he does know his stuff.

105
00:04:49,252 --> 00:04:51,085
After you wrap the body
in reflective tape,

106
00:04:51,087 --> 00:04:53,254
the ends get Teflon tape
so we can get a tight seal.

107
00:04:53,256 --> 00:04:55,389
Like this? Oh.
Yeah, perfect.

108
00:04:55,391 --> 00:04:57,124
And it helps to have
small, delicate fingers.

109
00:04:57,126 --> 00:04:58,726
So don't be discouraged
if you can't do it as fast

110
00:04:58,728 --> 00:05:00,361
as me and Howard. (chuckles)

111
00:05:01,697 --> 00:05:03,063
I don't know
if we have enough solder

112
00:05:03,065 --> 00:05:04,298
to finish
these circuit boards.

113
00:05:04,300 --> 00:05:05,529
We had a full spool yesterday.

114
00:05:05,530 --> 00:05:06,331
What can I say,

115
00:05:06,335 --> 00:05:08,936
I play hard,
I solder even harder.

116
00:05:10,506 --> 00:05:12,506
Sometimes he solders at home
with his shirt off.

117
00:05:12,508 --> 00:05:14,508
It's like a beer commercial.

118
00:05:14,510 --> 00:05:16,243
(blows, clicks tongue)

119
00:05:17,213 --> 00:05:19,213
Well, we got to make a run
to the hardware store.

120
00:05:19,215 --> 00:05:21,515
How can you call yourself a
scientist and run out of solder?

121
00:05:21,517 --> 00:05:24,318
Well, funny story.
So, we have plenty

122
00:05:24,320 --> 00:05:26,253
of the 60/40
tin-to-lead ratio solder,

123
00:05:26,255 --> 00:05:28,915
but the spools look a lot
like the 63/37 tin-to...

124
00:05:28,916 --> 00:05:29,555
Honey, honey,

125
00:05:29,559 --> 00:05:32,960
honey, let me stop you.
That is-is not a funny story.

126
00:05:34,096 --> 00:05:35,830
You want to come with us?

127
00:05:35,832 --> 00:05:37,355
I'm kind of getting
into the groove here.

128
00:05:37,356 --> 00:05:37,976
Yeah, you guys run

129
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:40,821
to the store and let the women
handle the science for a change.

130
00:05:40,822 --> 00:05:41,500
LEONARD: Okay.

131
00:05:41,504 --> 00:05:43,537
We'll be back
as soon as we can.

132
00:05:43,539 --> 00:05:46,807
(clears throat)
Okay, so what...

133
00:05:46,809 --> 00:05:49,009
is solder?

134
00:05:51,180 --> 00:05:54,148
I suppose I should
set this up.

135
00:05:54,150 --> 00:05:57,785
Or would you like
to rob me of that, too?

136
00:05:57,787 --> 00:06:00,754
